            "len": 33,
            "post_value": "https://linkedin.com/in/cyshekari"
          },
          {
            "id": "f716c08a-ece5-477f-9260-3a7117bf9e91_1230e70e-6868-4809-8965-c77601973fd8",
            "dom_id": "1230e70e-6868-4809-8965-c77601973fd8",
            "len": 25,
            "post_value": "https://github.com/cyshek"
          },
          {
            "id": "f716c08a-ece5-477f-9260-3a7117bf9e91_0b43208a-905a-45fb-84b5-154e673a0fe8",
            "dom_id": "0b43208a-905a-45fb-84b5-154e673a0fe8",
            "len": 1171,
            "post_value": "At Microsoft, I built an internal AI agent that automated drill planning workflows, cutting planning time by 39% and increasing drill capacity by 21%. That project, along with leading agentic AI adoption across 14 Azure service teams and architecting RAG-grounded semantic search that cut engineer lookup time by 83%, gave me a front-row seat to both the promise and the messiness of deploying generative AI inside large enterprises. I know what it takes to translate a technical capability into something that actually lands with Fortune 500 clients, and I want to do that at a company where that work is the core product, not a side initiative.\n\nWRITER's bet on end-to-end enterprise AI, grounded in company data and built for IT and business teams together, is the right architectural thesis. Most platforms bolt AI onto existing workflows; WRITER is building the orchestration layer from the ground up. That distinction matters, and it's the kind of problem I want to be close to. The customer roster, the focus on trust and grounding, and the speed at which the platform is moving all point to a place where a solutions architect can do genuinely high-leverage work."
          },
          {
            "id": "f716c08a-ece5-477f-9260-3a7117bf9e91_9776654b-fcbf-46fa-ba45-2183f2d5f5b6",
            "dom_id": "9776654b-fcbf-46fa-ba45-2183f2d5f5b6",
            "len": 1310,
            "post_value": "One example that comes to mind is the sovereign-cloud network isolation test I led at Microsoft, tied to a $1.5B+ enterprise contract. I was brought in as the bridge lead to direct 14 cross-org recovery executions under C-suite visibility. The technical complexity was real, involving coordinating across engineering, operations, and partner teams with strict isolation requirements, but the harder challenge was translating what was happening at the infrastructure level into narratives that executives could actually act on. I had to be precise without being opaque, and I had to move fast without cutting corners on accuracy.\n\nThat experience reflects something I try to bring consistently: a bias toward clarity and ownership in high-stakes situations. I did not wait for someone else to define the communication model or the recovery sequencing. I built both from scratch, aligned stakeholders across organizations, and made sure the outcomes were documented in a way that could inform future architecture decisions. The drill completed successfully, and the account relationship was strengthened because the customer felt informed and in control throughout. That kind of trust-building through technical transparency is something I take seriously and would carry into every customer engagement at WRITER."
          }
        ],
